      "source": [
        "Random Forest feature importance is measured differently from linear regression coefficients: a coefficient tells you the direction and dollar size of a feature's effect, while importance only tells you how much a feature reduced prediction error across all trees, regardless of direction. The two tables are not directly comparable line-by-line, but together they show whether the features that matter most for prediction (Model 3) line up with the features that push salary up or down (Model 2).\n",
        "\n",
        "This pattern is visible in the results above: Title dominates Model 2's coefficient table (e.g., \"data engineer analytics\" adds over \\$100,000), but no individual title appears in Model 3's top 20 importance list. This is not a contradiction -- it is a direct consequence of one-hot encoding. Title is split into 30+ separate columns, so its predictive contribution gets divided across all of them, while a single-column feature like Minimum Years Experience keeps its full contribution concentrated in one place. The apparent drop in Title's importance reflects how the feature is encoded, not a real loss of predictive value.\n",
